From 3565b726bb2e098d6bf87f297873f66a91b210d3 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Chronium Build <chronium@interlink.local>
Date: Mon, 8 Jun 2026 13:10:30 +0700
Subject: [PATCH 14/14] chronium: permissions.query DENIED -> ASK + per-profile
 font enumeration allowlist
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Two anti-detect surfaces in one patch.

Permissions.query (plan §5 #16)
  When a fingerprint profile is active and the platform returns
  DENIED for one of the cross-checked permissions (notifications,
  geolocation, audio/video capture, midi), the patch remaps the
  status to ASK before the JS promise resolves.

  Why: real Chrome on a fresh profile yields Notification.permission
  === 'default' AND permissions.query({name:'notifications'})
  resolving to 'prompt' (the JS spelling of ASK). Headless Chrome
  / bot stacks default these queries to 'denied' while leaving
  Notification.permission at 'default', which is the well-known
  inconsistency every modern fingerprinter (creepjs, fpjs2,
  pixelscan) flags as a hard automation signal.

  Verified: profile B query returns state 'prompt', and
  Notification.permission is 'default' — the pair the spec says a
  fresh user sees.

Font enumeration allowlist (plan §5 #9)
  FingerprintState gains SetFontsAllowlist / IsFontAllowed.
  FingerprintProfile parses the JSON 'fonts' array to a CSV string;
  the browser propagates as --fingerprint-fonts; the renderer
  installs into FingerprintState at RenderThreadStarted. FontCache::
  GetFontPlatformData returns nullptr early for any kCreateFontByFamily
  request whose family isn't in the allowlist, which makes
  ctx.measureText fall through the fallback chain to Arial.

  Match is case-insensitive ASCII. Empty allowlist = no restriction
  (so vanilla Chronium without a profile, or a profile with no
  'fonts' key, is unaffected).

  Verified on profile A (allowlist contains Arial, Calibri,
  Cambria, ...):
    measureText('Arial')        -> 109.376  (baseline)
    measureText('Calibri', ...) -> 101.701  (allowlisted, renders)
    measureText('FooBarFont')   -> 109.376  (denied -> Arial fallback)
    measureText('SomeRareFont') -> 109.376  (denied -> Arial fallback)

  Web fonts loaded via @font-face / <link rel=stylesheet> are
  unaffected: those go through CSSFontFaceSource / RemoteFontFaceSource
  rather than GetFontPlatformData-by-family-name, so pages that
  pull in their own webfonts still render correctly. Only LOCAL
  fonts referenced by family name are filtered, which is precisely
  what local-font fingerprinters key on.

